{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17496587","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17496587"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T08:51:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T08:51:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1386"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1386"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.06,0.38,0.38,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107687"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1386","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1386"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1386"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90119"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1040"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1139"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"4578"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"5469"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7116"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40144"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107687","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107687"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents to the emergency department with a four hour history of left sided flank pain radiating to his scrotum. He describes the pain as getting worse and coming and going in waves. His medical history is significant for diet-controlled type 2 diabetes and gout, the latter being treated with allopurinol. Whilst in the emergency department, he vomits several times. On examination, he appears restless and unwell. His blood pressure is 136/82 mmHg, pulse 110/min, respiratory rate 16/min and temperature 36.5\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. His abdomen is soft, with no localised tenderness. Urinalysis is positive for blood. He is given 100mg indomethacin rectally, but the pain unchanged. A CT scan is performed (Image) and shows an 11 mm stone.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Medical expulsion therapy","Nephrostomy insertion","Extracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy","Ureteroscopic extraction","Percutaneous nephrolithotomy"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient has presented with ureteric colic - the history is characteristic, and the presence of blood in his urine virtually confirms the diagnosis. The coronal section of the CT shows two calcified lesions. One is located in the lower part of the right pelvicalyceal collecting system, and the other is in the distal ureter.\u00a0The stone in the right kidney is small and not producing any obstruction and will remain asymptomatic unless it migrates distally and causes obstruction and distension of the renal capsule. The left-sided stone is causing a degree of obstruction, as evidenced by the clear visibility of hydronephrosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EImportant red flags in this type of presentation include the presence of fever and left loin tenderness, which are not reported in this case. These features would raise concern for an obstructed and infected system. Such a situation would demand urgent intervention and decompression with a ureteric stent\u003Cstrong\u003E.\u003C/strong\u003E A nephrostomy might be considered if the patient had severe sepsis and was too unstable for a general anaesthetic and stent placement.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EGiven the stone\u0027s size (approximately 11 mm), it is unlikely to pass spontaneously. In addition to providing adequate pain relief, active intervention is required. Some form of \u003Cstrong\u003Eureteroscopic extraction\u003C/strong\u003E should be undertaken. This could be done more expeditiously and efficiently than lithotripsy.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIf the stone was smaller (\u0026lt;6 mm), then \u003Cstrong\u003Emedical expulsion therapy\u003C/strong\u003E would be an appropriate initial step in the management. \u003Cstrong\u003EExtracorporeal shockwave lithotripsy\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative elective procedure that can be used for stones measuring up to approximately 2 cm. It has a lower stone-free rate and poorer clinical outcomes compared with ureteroscopy. \u003Cstrong\u003EPercutaneous nephrolithotomy\u003C/strong\u003E is the preferred choice for large renal calculi. This procedure has a higher stone-free rate compared with other approaches and is not limited by stone size or composition. This approach might also be considered in this patient (to decompress the hydronephrosis) if the stone could not be extracted ureteroscopically.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Ureteric stones greater than 7 mm are likely to require active intervention for their removal."],"references":["Akram M, Jahrresiss V, Skolarikos A, et al. Urological Guidelines for Kidney Stones: Overview and Comprehensive Update. J. Clin. Med. 2024, 13, 1114. Available from: https://www.mdpi.com/resolver?pii=jcm13041114"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90119"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1386"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"17417"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"17417","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/17417"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.co